Combine several phyloseq objects that describe the \strong{same set of samples}
sequenced with \strong{different markers} (e.g. 16S and ITS, or ITS1 and ITS2)
into a single phyloseq object. The result is assembled slot by slot with
full control (it does \emph{not} rely on \code{phyloseq::merge_phyloseq()}, which
merges phyloseq \emph{components} rather than whole objects):
\itemize{
\item \strong{Samples} are combined with a \emph{full join} of the \code{sam_data} slots: the
output keeps the union of all sample names and the union of all metadata
columns. A sample shared by two markers keeps a single row; for a shared
column, the first non-missing value across the input objects is used.
\item \strong{Taxa are never merged.} Taxa names are disambiguated by prefixing them
with the marker name (see \code{disambiguate_taxa}), so a taxon named \code{"ASV_1"}
in two markers becomes e.g. \code{"16S_ASV_1"} and \code{"ITS_ASV_1"} and stays as
two distinct taxa. The output \code{otu_table} is therefore the block-diagonal
union of the inputs.
\item A \strong{new \code{tax_table} column} (named by \code{marker_column}) records the marker
of origin for every taxon.
\item An \strong{occurrence} of a taxon in a sample that was not sequenced with that
taxon's marker is set to \code{0} (the taxon was simply not observable there).
\item \code{refseq} slots are concatenated when \emph{every} input object has one;
otherwise \code{refseq} is dropped with a warning. Phylogenetic trees cannot be
meaningfully merged across markers and are dropped with a warning.
}
}
\section{Do NOT post-cluster the result}{

The taxa carried by different markers are intentionally kept apart. You must
\strong{not} run any post-clustering step (e.g. \code{MiscMetabar::postcluster_pq()})
on the merged object, because that would collapse taxa coming from different
markers into a single taxon, mixing incomparable sequences (a 16S OTU and an
ITS OTU are not the same organism just because their sequences happen to be
similar). Keep the markers separate for any per-marker analysis and treat the
merged object as a \emph{stacked} view for cross-marker exploration.

The only legitimate cross-marker merging is at the \strong{taxonomy} level and
must be done explicitly on the \code{tax_table} (e.g. aggregating ITS1 and ITS2
taxa that resolve to the same species with \code{MiscMetabar::merge_taxa_vec()} or
\code{phyloseq::tax_glom()}), never through sequence-based clustering.
}

\examples{
library(phyloseq)

# Two tiny fake markers describing the same three samples ------------------
make_marker <- function(taxa, ranks) {
  otu <- matrix(
    sample(0:20, length(taxa) * 3, replace = TRUE),
    nrow = length(taxa),
    dimnames = list(taxa, c("samp1", "samp2", "samp3"))
  )
  tax <- matrix(
    paste(rep(ranks, each = length(taxa)), seq_along(taxa), sep = "_"),
    nrow = length(taxa),
    dimnames = list(taxa, ranks)
  )
  sam <- data.frame(
    row.names = c("samp1", "samp2", "samp3"),
    site = c("A", "A", "B"),
    depth = c(10, 20, 30)
  )
  phyloseq(
    otu_table(otu, taxa_are_rows = TRUE),
    tax_table(tax),
    sample_data(sam)
  )
}

pq_16S <- make_marker(c("ASV_1", "ASV_2"), c("Kingdom", "Phylum"))
# Note the SAME taxon name "ASV_1" reused in the ITS object:
pq_ITS <- make_marker(c("ASV_1", "ASV_3"), c("Kingdom", "Phylum", "Genus"))

merged <- merge_markers_pq(list("marker_16S" = pq_16S, "marker_ITS" = pq_ITS))

# Taxa are disambiguated and never merged: 4 taxa, not 3.
taxa_names(merged)
# The marker of origin is recorded in a new tax_table column.
tax_table(merged)[, "marker"]

# Providing marker names explicitly for an unnamed list:
merge_markers_pq(list(pq_16S, pq_ITS), marker_names = c("16S", "ITS"))

# WARNING: never post-cluster `merged` (e.g. MiscMetabar::postcluster_pq()).
# That would wrongly merge a 16S taxon with an ITS taxon.
